This page gives you guidance on how to stay safely in South Sudan as a visitor, if you are unable to return to the UK.
Everyone should comply with the measures put in place in South Sudan to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
Moving around in South Sudan
An official government curfew has been introduced across South Sudan from 8pm to 6am. Most shops, restaurants and businesses are closed. There are also restrictions on public transport, inter-state movements and public gatherings.
Keep up-to-date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans. If you need further information about entry requirements, see Entry requirements or contact the nearest South Sudan embassy. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Health
Your emotional and mental wellbeing is important. Read guidance on how to look after your mental wellbeing and mental health.
View Health for further details on healthcare in South Sudan.
See also the guidance on healthcare if youâ€™re waiting to return to the UK.
Finance
There is a range of financial support from the government that you can access while you are unable to return due to coronavirus restrictions.
For further UK government guidance on support you can access whilst abroad, visit our waiting to return guidance. This includes guidance on finance, health, and staying connected.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, contact the British Embassy Juba. All telephone numbers are available 24/7.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
